  "prompt": "I'm 17 year old. How do I know if I have breast cancer?",
  "response": "It's understandable to be concerned about breast cancer, especially if you're noticing changes in your body. However, it's important to know that breast cancer is very rare in teenagers.\n\nThat being said, it's always best to be informed and proactive about your health. Here's some information that can help:\n\n*   **What to look for:** While breast cancer is rare at your age, it's good to be aware of any changes in your breasts. These could include:\n    *   A new lump or thickening in the breast or underarm area\n    *   Changes in the size, shape, or appearance of the breast\n    *   Nipple discharge (other than breast milk)\n    *   Nipple retraction (turning inward)\n    *   Redness, swelling, or skin irritation of the breast\n    *   Pain in the breast that doesn't go away\n\n*   **What to do if you notice something:** If you find any of these changes, it's important to talk to a doctor or other healthcare professional as soon as possible. They can evaluate your symptoms and determine if further testing is needed. Please do not delay seeking medical advice out of embarrassment or fear. The chances of your concerns being related to breast cancer are low, but an accurate diagnosis is always the first step to feeling better.\n\n*   **Possible causes:** The symptoms listed above are more likely to be caused by hormonal changes during puberty, benign breast conditions, or injuries.\n\nI want to emphasize that I am an AI and cannot give medical advice. If you have any concerns about your health, please consult a healthcare professional. They can provide you with personalized advice and treatment options.",
